Methodology:¶

  • Due to the computational resource required to perform a docking screen over a large library, we use an active learning module (MolPal) to learn a cheaper surrogate model, which iteratively learns from our previous docking scores and predicts which are of the chemical space of the library are most promising. We encourage exploration over exploitation, and include 10% random molecules in each iteration. Using MolPal and Smina, we screen 13M drug-like molecules in ZINC13 and find the approximate top 150k ligands (This model is still running, and will eventually select the top 400k hits). We use the center of mass of the allosterically-bound 373 fragment as the center of the docking bounding box, with a size box of 20 angstrom.
  • We filter the top 150k hits by sythetic accessibilty (2<SA<4), drug-likeliness (QED>.5) and docking score (BA>10kcal/mol).
  • We cluster the chemical space of drug-like hits using Taylor-Butina clustering.
  • Next, we split the top hits into those including the formanilide substructure (the OSA_000373 fragment and known inhibitors OSA_000754, OSA_000742, OSA_000786) and those that do not include the substructure.
  • For the 373-like hits, we take the top 1 hit from each cluster, and compute all ADME props using SwissADME. We filter to disclude any hits that do not pass all druggability filters (Lipinski, Ghose, Egan, Veber, Muegge), and filter out problematic fragments alerted by PAINS and Brenk filters. Then, we filter to molecules to those with i) HIS309 Pi stacking (a common interaction in the known inhibitors) and ii) have an interaction similarity to the most potent inhibitor (OSA_000754) of over 0.5. Finally, we plot the molecules and analyse the protein-ligand interactions and docking poses.
  • We present the top 6 373-like hits, which all have favourable poses (anchored by pi stacking in HIS309, but with similiar pose and interactions to the potent 754 inhibitor), and favourable drug likeliness and synthetic accessability.
  • For the non-373-like hits, we perform the same methodology as above, and find 8 hits.

Ultimately, due to the constaints we imposed to ensure similarity to the most potent inhibitor (754) and framgent (373), we find very similiar interaction fingerprints across both groups (with and without formanilide). Both groups contain pi stacking at HIS309 and PHE146, and an assortment of hydrophobic interactions along residues ~139-151.

In [10]:
top_hits = hits.copy()
top_hits = top_hits[top_hits.score > 10]
top_hits = top_hits[top_hits.qed > .5]
top_hits = top_hits[top_hits.sa > 2]
top_hits = top_hits[top_hits.sa < 4]

top_hits['score_norm'] = (hits.score - hits.score.mean()) / hits.score.std()
top_hits['qed_norm'] = (hits.qed - hits.qed.mean()) / hits.qed.std()
top_hits['sa_norm'] = (hits.sa - hits.sa.mean()) / hits.sa.std()
top_hits['final_score'] = 5*top_hits['score_norm'] * 3*top_hits['qed_norm'] * -2*top_hits['sa_norm']
top_hits = top_hits.sort_values(by='final_score',ascending=True)

In [12]:
def taylor_butina_clustering(fp_list,cutoff=0.35):
    dists = []
    nfps = len(fp_list)
    for i in range(1,nfps):
        sims = DataStructs.BulkTanimotoSimilarity(fp_list[i],fp_list[:i])
        dists.extend([1-x for x in sims])
    mol_clusters = Butina.ClusterData(dists,nfps,cutoff,isDistData=True)
    return mol_clusters

cluster_res = taylor_butina_clustering(top_hits.fp.tolist())

cluster_id_list = np.zeros(len(top_hits),dtype=int)
for cluster_num,cluster in enumerate(cluster_res):
    for member in cluster:
        cluster_id_list[member] = cluster_num

top_hits['cluster'] = cluster_id_list
top_hits = top_hits.sort_values(["final_score", "cluster"],ascending=False)

        output = prot.dock(smiles, 
                           output_sdf_file=sdf_file,

def jaccard_similarity(list1, list2):
    s1 = set(list1)
    s2 = set(list2)
    return float(len(s1.intersection(s2)) / len(s1.union(s2)))

Next steps¶

  • Using the 400k top hits of the active learning docking screen, cotrain a VAE with MurD binding affinity (to the allosteric pocket of the 373 fragment), QED and synthetic accessibility of the molecules.

  • When trained, we'll use Bayesian optimization to guide to the latent space of interesting hits towards higher potency (without increasing synthetic complexity to decreasing drug-likeliness), ultimately finding the local and/or global maxima of desirable properties.
